WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.124 --> 00:00:02.040
BRAHIM ELBOUCHIKHI: Good
afternoon, everybody.

00:00:02.040 --> 00:00:03.360
My name is Brahim Elbouchikhi.

00:00:03.360 --> 00:00:05.930
I'm a product manager
on the Daydream team,

00:00:05.930 --> 00:00:09.670
and I'm responsible
for Play Store VR.

00:00:09.670 --> 00:00:14.080
I've been pretty fortunate to
work on ecosystem formation

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:15.800
for the past five years.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:17.590
Before this, I
was on Google Play

00:00:17.590 --> 00:00:20.480
for four years, where I
led monetization, search,

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:22.140
and discovery.

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:23.930
And I don't know how
many of you remember

00:00:23.930 --> 00:00:26.300
Android Market, and then
within Android market,

00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:30.260
the 10B sale, which is when
we turned all the apps to be

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:33.410
10 cents and then we had a
sale, and all this good stuff.

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:35.660
And I don't know if you
remember-- the store fell over

00:00:35.660 --> 00:00:37.220
within like two
hours of the sale

00:00:37.220 --> 00:00:39.170
because we couldn't
handle the traffic.

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:42.760
And that was a really bad
day for me and my team.

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:45.180
Now, we've come a long
way from there, right?

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:47.267
So Google Play is a much
more stable platform.

00:00:47.267 --> 00:00:48.850
We've got payments
all over the world,

00:00:48.850 --> 00:00:50.250
we've got users
spending billions

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:52.100
of dollars buying your content.

00:00:52.100 --> 00:00:54.200
We've come a long way,
and what attracted

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:57.800
me to come into VR and
Daydream is the opportunities

00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:00.590
to work with you again to figure
out some similar questions,

00:01:00.590 --> 00:01:03.090
but in an entirely
different context.

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:05.519
If you think of back
then, we were thinking

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:07.300
of how will I monetize my app?

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:09.150
How will I keep my users around?

00:01:09.150 --> 00:01:11.940
How do I do a user acquisition?

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:13.720
What content would
actually stick?

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:17.320
And those questions are
very much open today in VR.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:20.860
They are an entirely
open field for us

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:23.810
as a group to figure
out, and to build

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:29.690
those big brands in VR and on
Daydream as we have on mobile.

00:01:29.690 --> 00:01:33.140
So the hope is that
if in five years,

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:36.660
we're collectively working on
another frontier technology,

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:38.960
that we can look back
and then say again

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:41.750
that we've created value,
that we went past the hype

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:44.460
and actually delivered
real value for users,

00:01:44.460 --> 00:01:48.460
and built a multibillion
dollar business on Daydream.

00:01:48.460 --> 00:01:49.290
That's the goal.

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.150
That's why we had
this session today.

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:54.360
And I can't wait to kind of
get started and kind of start

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:56.060
working with you on this.

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:59.600
So a recap of Daydream, right?

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:02.290
So you've heard this from
Clay at the first keynote

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:03.500
this morning.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.680
Daydream is just
incredibly exciting for us

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:08.270
to start to tell you
the story of Daydream.

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:10.389
I have been working on
it for quite some time,

00:02:10.389 --> 00:02:13.730
and the team has been incredibly
thoughtful about thinking

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:17.780
about the various aspects
that create a high quality VR

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:18.760
experience.

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:20.740
So we've got the
smartphone, which

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:23.750
is at the core of the
experience, obviously.

00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:25.990
We've got a headset
that's comfortable,

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:28.290
we've got a controller
that can allow

00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:31.407
you to create really immersive
and awesome experiences,

00:02:31.407 --> 00:02:32.990
and then you've got
the apps, which is

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:34.510
what we're here to talk about.

00:02:34.510 --> 00:02:38.410
That's where we fit
in in this talk.

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:40.440
Now, just before we
get started, it's

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:42.880
important to step back and
talk about Google Play.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:45.490
I mentioned it's
a stable platform,

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:48.211
and Daydream is essentially
built on top of Google Play.

00:02:48.211 --> 00:02:48.710
Right?

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:50.520
It's our distribution platform.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:52.770
We, in a way, get
it for free, which

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.000
is an amazing asset to have.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.250
We got ahead 190 countries
where you distribute

00:02:57.250 --> 00:03:00.340
free apps, 130 countries
where you can sell your apps,

00:03:00.340 --> 00:03:03.640
and we've got the one
billion 30-day active users

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.220
that Google Play has.

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:07.880
Now, before anybody
yells it out,

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:09.390
those are not VR users today.

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:11.500
I'm not trying to
make that claim.

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:14.410
What I am going to say is
that at Daydream, we're

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.220
trying to operate
at Android scale.

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:20.220
That our intention is to
operate at Android scale,

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:24.940
meaning hundreds of millions of
users using Daydream devices.

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:29.010
And the way we get there is
through the typical smartphone

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:31.990
evolution where today's
premium devices,

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.460
the ones that can
run VR experiences,

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:38.210
are next year's mid-range,
and the following year's

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:40.610
potentially even
low end devices.

00:03:40.610 --> 00:03:42.920
So if you take
that evolution, you

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:45.510
can see that in a
couple years, we

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:48.510
will have hundreds
of millions of users

00:03:48.510 --> 00:03:50.820
on Daydream-ready
devices that are

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:54.250
ready to consume the mobile
VR experiences that you all

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:55.640
are going to build.

00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:57.200
But the main point
is the intention

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.590
is to operate at
Android scale, to have

00:03:59.590 --> 00:04:02.970
an ecosystem of devices,
of content creators,

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:06.230
and of partners creating
headsets and controllers.

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:06.730
All right.

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:12.290
So with that in mind,
I remember back then,

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:14.640
I used to meet a lot of
developers for mobile

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:16.500
and we used to have a
lot of conversations

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:19.880
around monetization,
discovery, et cetera.

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:21.589
And in this talk,
we tried to try

00:04:21.589 --> 00:04:24.860
to get ahead of some of those
questions that you have.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:26.920
We tried to pull user
studies that we've

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:30.270
had with some fairly large
numbers of users of mobile VR

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:32.990
and distill those into insights
that can be useful to you

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:35.910
at this stage of
your app development.

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:38.260
We've also looked at
data that we have,

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:40.320
and we've talked to many
of you, and we've also

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:42.480
talked honestly
amongst ourselves

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:45.456
and debated for a long,
long time to say, OK.

00:04:45.456 --> 00:04:46.830
Based on our
expertise, we've got

00:04:46.830 --> 00:04:48.788
people coming from console
world, people coming

00:04:48.788 --> 00:04:50.810
from mobile, people
coming from all sorts

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:53.010
of different
backgrounds thinking

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:58.370
about how is VR potentially
going to evolve from here.

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:00.629
Nobody knows the answers
to a lot of these things,

00:05:00.629 --> 00:05:02.670
but we hope that these
insights can at least help

00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:05.000
get the conversation
going and help us thinking

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.991
about the right set of things.

00:05:06.991 --> 00:05:07.490
All right.

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:09.590
So with that, I'm going
to jump in and talk

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:12.510
about the first insight.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:13.260
OK.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:16.960
So with mobile, you're
generally dealing

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:19.190
with a fairly distracted user.

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:20.970
They are at a bus station.

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:23.990
They are waiting for a
friend and killing some time.

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:27.020
They're interacting with your
app multiple times a day,

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:29.960
but fairly in short
interactions, a couple minutes.

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:30.640
Right?

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:33.190
And because of that,
mobile has evolved

00:05:33.190 --> 00:05:35.530
into free-to-play mechanics,
and all sorts of things

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:38.690
that kind of have derived
from that user behavior.

00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:40.480
That's great.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.210
When you think of
mobile VR, it's

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:44.380
an entirely different setting.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:47.300
Our studies showed that
users are spending 30 minutes

00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:50.400
plus in each session,
that they're also

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:54.740
having a single session a day,
not multiple sessions a day,

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:56.191
that they're doing this at home.

00:05:56.191 --> 00:05:58.190
No one is wearing these
headsets in the streets.

00:05:58.190 --> 00:05:59.590
Just FYI.

00:05:59.590 --> 00:06:00.090
Right?

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:01.350
Nobody is.

00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:03.050
Probably nobody will.

00:06:03.050 --> 00:06:05.312
It's at home, long sessions.

00:06:05.312 --> 00:06:06.770
Actually, we've
had photos of users

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:08.811
that kind of like lean
back, kind of like they're

00:06:08.811 --> 00:06:09.650
watching TV.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:11.420
That's the state of
mind of the user.

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:14.580
They're waiting to be, in
a way, kind of immersed

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:17.555
to be drawn into really
rich content that

00:06:17.555 --> 00:06:21.110
has a lot of narrative, and
they're in that state of mind.

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:23.970
And so as you build
your apps, the way

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:26.030
we try to synthesize
this is to say,

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:29.500
think a sit down
meal, not a snack.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:31.920
And sit down meals come
with certain expectations

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:37.510
of duration, of deliciousness
of the food, and also of cost.

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:40.290
So when you design
your app, while we

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:42.400
think of mobile as
a snack, mobile VR

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:44.590
is more of a sit down meal.

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:46.131
Just as a thing.

00:06:46.131 --> 00:06:46.630
All right.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:49.860
So the second insight.

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:50.880
This is an old chart.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:52.640
I used this chart
for a couple of years

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:56.080
now to demonstrate the
importance of quality

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:57.554
to monetization.

00:06:57.554 --> 00:06:58.970
And it's totally
intuitive, right?

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:01.010
If you build higher
quality content,

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:03.029
you will have more monetization.

00:07:03.029 --> 00:07:03.820
You will make more.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:05.480
People will pay more for that.

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:06.990
Nothing surprising here.

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:09.150
The scale is a bit surprising.

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:12.350
And in VR, we all know
that quality's going

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:13.434
to be even more important.

00:07:13.434 --> 00:07:13.933
Right?

00:07:13.933 --> 00:07:16.250
It's an order of magnitude,
probably, more important,

00:07:16.250 --> 00:07:18.240
because you can literally
make people feel bad,

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:20.810
like physically sick.

00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:23.710
So Alice is going to dive
into this much more later,

00:07:23.710 --> 00:07:28.440
so what I want to talk about,
however, is first impressions.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:33.400
So as an industry, we're
in those early days, right?

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:37.570
And we have a ton of first
time users coming through.

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:41.136
And each time a first time user
experiences one of your apps,

00:07:41.136 --> 00:07:42.510
there are two ways
it can happen.

00:07:42.510 --> 00:07:43.635
Two things that can happen.

00:07:43.635 --> 00:07:46.210
They can either become an
advocate for the industry,

00:07:46.210 --> 00:07:48.640
and spread the industry and
the fact that it's awesome,

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:51.220
and tell their friends and
family that, hey, VR is here.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:51.970
It's real.

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:53.640
It's awesome.

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:57.120
Or, they can either
confirm their skepticism

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:00.260
or become a skeptic by
saying it's not ready,

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:03.670
and potentially walking
away from VR for years.

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:07.430
For us as an industry,
not just for that one app.

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:10.580
And so the insight is,
as you design your apps,

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:11.390
think of that.

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:13.350
Think of the fact that
many of our users,

00:08:13.350 --> 00:08:16.970
as we move into the mainstream,
are first time users.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:19.260
Meaning that the experience
needs to hand-hold them

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:22.350
through what VR is, to
not like immediately

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:25.831
drop them in the deep
end of a VR experience,

00:08:25.831 --> 00:08:27.830
to make sure you introduce
them to these things,

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:30.030
to the mechanics,
to the experience.

00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:33.780
Be thoughtful about it, and
know that we're collectively

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:36.650
responsible for the
success of the industry.

00:08:36.650 --> 00:08:37.460
Right?

00:08:37.460 --> 00:08:40.890
If these things don't
catch, if the word of mouth

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:42.870
doesn't allow people
to get excited,

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:45.240
the people don't
speak well of VR,

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:47.590
we won't have a
successful industry.

00:08:47.590 --> 00:08:51.100
So that's the second
thing I wanted to share.

00:08:51.100 --> 00:08:55.320
The third thing
is about novelty.

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:57.930
And VR is incredibly
novel right now.

00:08:57.930 --> 00:08:58.430
Right?

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:00.820
I mean, one of the most
fun things you can do in VR

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:03.450
is show VR to people who've
never seen it before.

00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:03.950
Right?

00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:05.950
I mean, literally, demoing
VR is one of the most

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:08.490
fun you can do in VR.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:11.720
And it's really easy
and somewhat tempting

00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:15.840
to just say, oh, I'm going to
drop someone somewhere amazing

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:17.650
and be like, that's awesome.

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:19.330
That's a great experience.

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:21.870
That is a great
experience for 30 seconds.

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:23.890
And then as soon as
you achieve presence

00:09:23.890 --> 00:09:26.880
and you achieve like, oh my god,
I'm in space, you're like, OK.

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.354
What can I do?

00:09:28.354 --> 00:09:31.020
You look around again and you're
like, oh, can I touch anything?

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:31.840
No.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:34.540
And users don't engage further.

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:37.160
Users will not pay for novelty.

00:09:37.160 --> 00:09:39.120
Users will not pay for novelty.

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.250
Users pay for
engaging experiences.

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:43.390
And so when we designed
the Daydream controller,

00:09:43.390 --> 00:09:45.080
we had this
specifically in mind.

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:47.370
We wanted to give you
a tool that you can

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:49.600
use to create engaging content.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:51.610
So if you're going
to drop me in space,

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:55.190
make sure I can point at any
planet and learn about it.

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:59.840
Or maybe I can grab a planet
and toss it out of the galaxy.

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:04.060
Help me do something there and
go beyond the novelty of VR,

00:10:04.060 --> 00:10:09.360
because that's the easy
path is to use the novelty.

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:11.512
The fourth insight.

00:10:11.512 --> 00:10:12.474
Ah.

00:10:12.474 --> 00:10:13.920
Oh.

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:14.880
I went too far.

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:19.540
OK, so the fourth insight is
about-- I learned this actually

00:10:19.540 --> 00:10:21.910
when I was in mobile,
and on the Play Store,

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:23.620
we used to get a
lot of people that

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:26.970
run these queries like a
search query that says game.

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:28.330
App.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:29.407
That's it.

00:10:29.407 --> 00:10:31.490
And we struggle with what--
that's there-- there's

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:32.700
very little intent there.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:35.990
There's very little we can do
to help the user in the search

00:10:35.990 --> 00:10:38.996
results, because
it's so high level.

00:10:38.996 --> 00:10:40.620
And we've learned
that that's basically

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:42.920
new users who don't understand
what their device is

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:45.070
capable of, or new
users who don't

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:48.000
know how to search for things.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.420
What are the words I need
to put to actually search

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:52.420
for the right content?

00:10:52.420 --> 00:10:54.410
And the insight
here is, I believe

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:57.540
that the entire industry
in VR is in that stage,

00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:01.930
that we all-- there's no
evolved, clear taxonomy of how

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:04.260
we describe these
experiences and these apps.

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:07.480
We don't have clear
expectations of what

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:10.980
actually can be achieved in VR.

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:14.920
For example, a
teleportation app.

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:17.190
Is that a travel app?

00:11:17.190 --> 00:11:20.540
It could be, but I doubt anybody
will search for travel app

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:22.870
when they want to find
a teleportation app.

00:11:22.870 --> 00:11:25.760
So because of that, what
you need to think of

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:28.310
is that users are in their
window shopping mode,

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.870
not in a grocery shopping mode.

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:33.390
And what that means is,
we've gotten used in mobile

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:35.720
now where users come with
a specific thing they're

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:36.960
looking for.

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:38.470
They go and they
type specifically

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:39.550
what they're looking for.

00:11:39.550 --> 00:11:41.230
Most users are at
that stage now,

00:11:41.230 --> 00:11:43.770
because they're familiar with
what a smartphone can do.

00:11:43.770 --> 00:11:45.660
But in VR, a lot of
users are going to come

00:11:45.660 --> 00:11:47.889
and they're going to wait
to be dazzled by the app.

00:11:47.889 --> 00:11:48.680
What is this about?

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:49.660
What can it do?

00:11:49.660 --> 00:11:52.910
So as you design, whether in
the store, in the Play Store,

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.350
or out on the web, or
your YouTube trailers,

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:58.280
your 360 trailers for your
app-- whatever you do,

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:01.710
make sure you realize that
the users' state of mind when

00:12:01.710 --> 00:12:04.570
they are looking for
apps at this point in VR

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:06.180
is very undefined.

00:12:06.180 --> 00:12:07.260
It's very high level.

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:10.160
They're kind of more on the
receiving end, browsing, window

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:10.970
shopping.

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:12.428
They don't know
something specific.

00:12:12.428 --> 00:12:15.620
They're not looking
for something specific.

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:17.480
So that's another one.

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:26.610
The fifth insight is that VR
is meant to be experienced.

00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:31.280
And I'm going to unpack
it for you a bit.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:33.090
A lot of technologies,
it's really easy

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:34.720
to describe them in words.

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:37.220
So for example, if you go
to describe 3D printing

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:40.340
to someone, you could
just say, well, you know,

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:42.910
this thing was made,
probably in China,

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:44.790
and then it got
shipped to your house.

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:48.040
Instead of that, you can have a
CAD model and you can hit Print

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.116
and it just shows
up at your home.

00:12:50.116 --> 00:12:50.990
Right on the printer.

00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:51.490
Right?

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:54.250
And the people kind of
get what it's about.

00:12:54.250 --> 00:12:56.740
Now, when you try to
describe VR to someone,

00:12:56.740 --> 00:12:59.514
you tell them, well, you
feel like you're there.

00:12:59.514 --> 00:13:01.680
And they kind of look at
you and they're like, well,

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:03.222
but I'm not there.

00:13:03.222 --> 00:13:05.180
But then you say, well,
no, but then, you know,

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:09.002
you're-- we have two different
images in your eyes, we have--

00:13:09.002 --> 00:13:10.960
we introduce parallax,
as so you can see depth.

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:13.810
And then you have head tracking,
and motion and photo on just

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:15.340
for fun.

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:18.590
And you talk about all
these things and the user,

00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:22.200
they don't really get
it, most of the time.

00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:25.680
And so what you need is you need
someone to experience your app.

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:28.649
They need to actually be in it
to understand what it's about.

00:13:28.649 --> 00:13:29.690
And this doesn't go away.

00:13:29.690 --> 00:13:32.550
This actually stays for
every single experience

00:13:32.550 --> 00:13:36.350
that I'm going to try to engage
with, or buy, or install.

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:40.180
I'm going to want to
experience it before I do that.

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:44.960
So the insight here is,
make sure you give users

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:48.000
ways to try and
experience your app

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.750
before they have to
increase their commitment.

00:13:50.750 --> 00:13:53.330
So if it's basically
a large install,

00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:56.420
if I have to download
500 megs Before I even

00:13:56.420 --> 00:13:59.560
know what your thing is
about, I'm not going to do it.

00:13:59.560 --> 00:14:02.220
If potentially I
need to pay upfront

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:06.450
without even seeing a 360
YouTube trailer about your app,

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:08.040
I may not do it.

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:11.070
So think about ways that
you can introduce the user

00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:14.490
to what your experience
is about before asking

00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:15.868
them to take that next step.

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:23.390
Our final insight here is
about purchasing and purchasing

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:23.890
behavior.

00:14:26.387 --> 00:14:27.970
If you look back at
everything we just

00:14:27.970 --> 00:14:30.300
talked about now,
the fact that you

00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:35.780
have a single session a day, the
fact that you have a user who's

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:38.790
immersed-- meaning that
purchasing is going to probably

00:14:38.790 --> 00:14:39.770
break that immersion.

00:14:39.770 --> 00:14:41.326
It's going to get in the way.

00:14:41.326 --> 00:14:43.200
If you think about a
lot of these things that

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.230
make VR so awesome,
you're not going

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:48.760
to want to have things like
free-to-play mechanics, energy

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:50.850
mechanics, time-based mechanics.

00:14:50.850 --> 00:14:54.500
It's just not going to
work, in all likelihood.

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:55.650
Things may change.

00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:58.510
But it's going to be hard.

00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:01.130
And so what we're recommending
is an experience where

00:15:01.130 --> 00:15:04.880
a user is able to
unlock the entire thing

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:09.770
with a single purchase, and that
purchase can be an in-app where

00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:11.770
basically, I try
a couple levels,

00:15:11.770 --> 00:15:14.910
I get what your app is
about, I experience it,

00:15:14.910 --> 00:15:17.620
and then I make a
purchase to unlock

00:15:17.620 --> 00:15:19.270
the remainder of the app.

00:15:19.270 --> 00:15:23.210
That balances out both the I
need to try it before I buy,

00:15:23.210 --> 00:15:26.860
but it also does not disrupt the
experience on a regular basis.

00:15:26.860 --> 00:15:29.620
It doesn't try that recurring
monetization loop that's

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:33.900
become so familiar in mobile.

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:34.400
OK.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:39.480
So to summarize, we would
like you to build high quality

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:43.820
content that has
narrative, that's

00:15:43.820 --> 00:15:47.650
equivalent to a beautiful,
awesome book that draws you in

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:50.260
and that you can't put down.

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:53.300
We want you to engage
with users beyond novelty,

00:15:53.300 --> 00:15:56.230
because no one pays for novelty.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:58.350
If you find someone,
let me know.

00:15:58.350 --> 00:16:02.660
Let users try your
experience before they

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.870
need to take that next
step of commitment.

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:09.380
And finally, think of
ways to allow a user

00:16:09.380 --> 00:16:12.362
to make a single purchase to
unlock an entire experience.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:20.310
Keeping in mind that free to
play may be challenged in VR.

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:21.840
OK.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.230
So with that, I want to move on
to the next part of this talk,

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:29.290
which is Play Store in VR.

00:16:29.290 --> 00:16:31.030
You've seen some of
these bits and pieces

00:16:31.030 --> 00:16:32.650
through the keynotes
and the videos

00:16:32.650 --> 00:16:34.066
and all that sort
of stuff, so I'm

00:16:34.066 --> 00:16:36.100
going to go through
them fairly quickly.

00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:42.220
This is what we
call Daydream Home.

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:44.640
When the user boots into
VR, they're automatically

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:47.330
dropped into this environment.

00:16:47.330 --> 00:16:50.620
The one thing I want to
highlight here is the icon.

00:16:50.620 --> 00:16:52.900
People are familiar
with the Play Store.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:56.500
This is the same place
I get my 2D apps,

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:59.368
it's the same place that
I make my purchases,

00:16:59.368 --> 00:17:01.618
and it's the same place I'm
going to do it here in VR.

00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:08.140
Now, I don't know
if we'll launch

00:17:08.140 --> 00:17:09.598
with this background
in particular,

00:17:09.598 --> 00:17:12.349
but I got to tell you that
the team is thinking really

00:17:12.349 --> 00:17:15.640
about fun spaces
that are unusual,

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:18.819
that are representative
of the immersion of VR,

00:17:18.819 --> 00:17:22.670
that just create a really
nice feel and really fun feel.

00:17:22.670 --> 00:17:24.630
So they explain a
lot of those things.

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:26.920
And of course, 2D
does it no justice

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:31.920
in terms of when you see a 2D
screen shot of a VR experience,

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:33.870
again, going back to
the earlier point.

00:17:33.870 --> 00:17:37.890
So what you notice here is
content is front and center.

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:38.390
Right?

00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:40.240
This is our featured
port in the store,

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:42.460
and you have that
beautiful poster

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:45.890
that has depth, that allows
somebody to kind of get

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:48.750
into what is this about,
as much as we can, at least

00:17:48.750 --> 00:17:51.300
at this stage.

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:52.900
You also see the
store representing

00:17:52.900 --> 00:17:56.010
what I talked about in terms
of the lack of categories

00:17:56.010 --> 00:17:57.180
or taxonomy.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:00.540
At launch, it's going
to be pretty simple.

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:04.087
You're not going to see tons
of categories, different words

00:18:04.087 --> 00:18:04.920
being thrown around.

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:08.040
It's going to be simple, and
we need to keep it simple.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:09.810
At the bottom, we
have four sections.

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:12.380
The Featured section,
which is curated.

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:14.120
You've got the
Popular section, which

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:16.990
is top charts, essentially,
and then you have two homes

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:19.440
for apps and for games.

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:22.670
As we learn more about what
sort of content types--

00:18:22.670 --> 00:18:24.700
and Alice is going to
talk more about that--

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:28.460
are going to emerge, we
will have the store evolve,

00:18:28.460 --> 00:18:33.210
but to start with, we're
starting and keeping it simple.

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:35.640
Next is Popular, right?

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:41.030
So even here, we're given a lot
more space for a single item.

00:18:41.030 --> 00:18:42.750
It's not so much
of the compressed,

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:44.730
let's have a whole chart
stacked up together

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:47.400
so we can fit as many things
as we can on the screen.

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:49.030
Here, even though
we have more space,

00:18:49.030 --> 00:18:51.380
we're actually showing
fewer things at a time.

00:18:51.380 --> 00:18:53.860
Because again, that window
shopping experience.

00:18:53.860 --> 00:18:57.460
We want someone to be able to
understand what your app is

00:18:57.460 --> 00:19:00.640
about one at a time and
just really kind of get

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:04.450
to the next level of commitment,
hopefully, making a purchase

00:19:04.450 --> 00:19:05.440
or installing the app.

00:19:07.950 --> 00:19:09.580
Lindsay this morning
also showed us

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:13.357
this, which is the Details page.

00:19:13.357 --> 00:19:14.940
And the thing I want
to highlight here

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:18.750
is the photosphere, that 360
degree stereoscopic image.

00:19:18.750 --> 00:19:20.480
We're doing this,
again, to try to help

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:22.650
with the trying the experience.

00:19:22.650 --> 00:19:24.650
I don't think this is
necessarily like entirely

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:27.900
trying it, but it gets us
one step closer to the user

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:31.090
being able to look around
and see what this is about.

00:19:31.090 --> 00:19:34.720
Having tried this, it really
is effective in making

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:38.560
sure you understand what
this app is about as a user.

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:41.710
So we're doing
this and every app

00:19:41.710 --> 00:19:46.440
will need to submit this
particular photosphere.

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:49.620
Finally, we will support
in-app purchases,

00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:52.430
and they will work exactly as
you would expect them to work.

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:56.370
All right.

00:19:56.370 --> 00:20:02.260
So Cardboard apps were
about fun, snackable,

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:06.640
short experiences, largely
non-interactive, right?

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:10.480
The one button, they
were kept very simple.

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:13.600
Daydream apps are
quite the opposite.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:19.680
They're about immersive content,
long form, highly interactive.

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:23.390
The Daydream controller
is key to the last bit.

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:25.660
And the best metaphor
that I can think

00:20:25.660 --> 00:20:29.990
of for it is a book that
is incredibly awesome that

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:33.900
draws you in, and
that you get lost in.

00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:35.380
It's happened to
every one of us,

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:37.840
where there's some book
you just can't put down.

00:20:37.840 --> 00:20:40.850
That's our ideal Daydream app.

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:42.740
And this is a side
thing I was thinking

00:20:42.740 --> 00:20:44.800
about when I was rehearsing.

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:47.450
The fact that a book
made out of paper

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:49.980
can do that your
brain and can actually

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:52.760
get you to imagine
things and picture them

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:55.450
in your mind as
clear as if you're

00:20:55.450 --> 00:20:57.740
looking at them-- the
fact that a book on paper

00:20:57.740 --> 00:21:01.030
can do that is
absolutely ridiculous.

00:21:01.030 --> 00:21:03.070
It's absolutely amazing, right?

00:21:03.070 --> 00:21:06.140
So if you combine that with
a medium that literally

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.930
is meant to make you immersed,
and to actually visualize

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:11.450
all these things--
if you combine

00:21:11.450 --> 00:21:17.997
that kind of powerful
narrative with VR as a medium,

00:21:17.997 --> 00:21:19.830
it's absolutely amazing
what can be created,

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:22.680
and that's what keeps us really
excited about the potential

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:24.960
of this space.

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:28.770
So with that in
mind, we have a bunch

00:21:28.770 --> 00:21:31.410
of talks today and
tomorrow that are

00:21:31.410 --> 00:21:33.590
going to try to show you
how to build for Daydream.

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:36.930
In fact, we've learned
there was the prototyping

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:39.400
talk this morning,
Daydream controller talk

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:42.960
next, there is tomorrow's
Designing for Daydream,

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:45.340
there is the high performance
app development tomorrow

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:46.200
as well.

00:21:46.200 --> 00:21:47.866
So all those talks
are going to tell you

00:21:47.866 --> 00:21:51.020
how to build a Daydream app, or
at least some insights into it.

00:21:51.020 --> 00:21:53.090
I'm going to talk about
the boring part, which

00:21:53.090 --> 00:21:56.630
is how do you get your app to
be technically a Daydream app.

00:21:56.630 --> 00:21:59.100
Like how do we change
the manifest to actually

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:00.980
make it a Daydream app.

00:22:00.980 --> 00:22:02.805
So this is a manifest.

00:22:02.805 --> 00:22:05.420
A truncated, Android
app manifest.

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:07.135
And it's for a Daydream app.

00:22:07.135 --> 00:22:08.510
Now, what I'm
going to do is, I'm

00:22:08.510 --> 00:22:10.730
going to walk through
a few of these things

00:22:10.730 --> 00:22:13.870
and highlight some
bits and pieces.

00:22:13.870 --> 00:22:16.880
These two feature
tags tell Android

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:20.320
that you're using both
the software and hardware

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:21.528
features of Daydream.

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:28.930
This particular thing, this
tag in your activity block

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:33.610
tells the system that you want
to launch directly into VR,

00:22:33.610 --> 00:22:35.680
because you don't want
any sort of race condition

00:22:35.680 --> 00:22:38.320
or any kind of
transition from 2D to VR.

00:22:38.320 --> 00:22:41.430
And so because of that, you
put this in your activity block

00:22:41.430 --> 00:22:44.890
to tell Android that I
am an entirely VR app.

00:22:44.890 --> 00:22:50.850
I'm only useful in VR, so
trigger me into VR directly.

00:22:50.850 --> 00:22:54.480
This is how you specify the two
icon assets I've showed you.

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:56.850
Alex is going to show you a
nice visualization of them,

00:22:56.850 --> 00:22:59.610
but basically, in the manifest,
you set these two icons

00:22:59.610 --> 00:23:03.880
and you upload the
360 degree image.

00:23:03.880 --> 00:23:06.870
Now I'm going to introduce this
concept of a self-contained VR

00:23:06.870 --> 00:23:08.230
environment.

00:23:08.230 --> 00:23:10.460
And we couldn't come
up with a shorter name.

00:23:10.460 --> 00:23:13.120
If you have ideas, let me
know, but basically, it's

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:15.780
something where you can
navigate the entire experience

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:19.190
without running into 2D flows.

00:23:19.190 --> 00:23:23.327
If there are 2D flows, you want
them to be graciously handled,

00:23:23.327 --> 00:23:25.160
meaning that the user
is told that they need

00:23:25.160 --> 00:23:27.560
to take their phone
off for some reason,

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:29.570
and it needs to be
an exceptional thing.

00:23:29.570 --> 00:23:34.400
It can be a regular
part of use of the app.

00:23:34.400 --> 00:23:37.290
And so the key here, this
is the manifest entry

00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:39.520
to tell us what that intent is.

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:42.290
This is the Daydream intent,
and it's a new intent filter

00:23:42.290 --> 00:23:45.170
category.

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:47.930
So with that, you
have a Daydream app.

00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:50.420
You have an app that's
built from the ground up

00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:52.290
to be for Daydream.

00:23:52.290 --> 00:23:55.470
It's immersive, it's long
form, it's interactive,

00:23:55.470 --> 00:23:57.670
it takes advantage of
the hardware and software

00:23:57.670 --> 00:23:59.040
features of the platform.

00:23:59.040 --> 00:23:59.770
It is awesome.

00:23:59.770 --> 00:24:03.870
It's that beautiful book
that we talked about.

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:05.690
But there is more, right?

