And Android yesterday announced
that they've had 65 billion

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:16.950
downloads in 12 months, which
is ridiculous if you think of it

00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:18.680
in the context of
the $0.10 promo,

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:22.370
where we had all time 10 billion
at a time and were super happy.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:26.110
This is 65 billion in 12 months.

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:29.290
And we know that many of
you have users on Android.

00:24:29.290 --> 00:24:31.920
You have millions, tens of
millions, hundreds of millions

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:35.520
of users already using
your apps on Android.

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:38.120
So its important for us
to allow you to introduce

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:42.020
Daydream experiences
to your existing apps.

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:44.690
And so we have a
concept of a hybrid app,

00:24:44.690 --> 00:24:46.020
and its going to show up.

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:50.660
A hybrid app is an app that has
both 2D flows and a Daydream

00:24:50.660 --> 00:24:52.410
experience.

00:24:52.410 --> 00:24:55.330
Now, the Daydream
experience comes to life

00:24:55.330 --> 00:24:57.630
on a Daydream-ready device.

00:24:57.630 --> 00:25:02.262
The 2D flows are
available on every device.

00:25:02.262 --> 00:25:03.720
The Play Movie's
team, for example,

00:25:03.720 --> 00:25:06.980
when they considered building
a Daydream experience,

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:10.260
they have decided to add it to
their existing Play Movies app.

00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:14.750
This does some
really awesome stuff.

00:25:14.750 --> 00:25:18.120
Because what this does is it
aligns your development costs,

00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:22.280
and it aligns your
user acquisition costs,

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:24.470
and finally, it
allows you to take

00:25:24.470 --> 00:25:26.230
advantage of this
large user base

00:25:26.230 --> 00:25:28.980
you already have on Android.

00:25:28.980 --> 00:25:30.300
So this is super critical.

00:25:30.300 --> 00:25:33.220
And the way you do it
is incredibly easy.

00:25:33.220 --> 00:25:36.560
You just turn that flag--
the Android Required False--

00:25:36.560 --> 00:25:39.390
you turn it from true to false.

00:25:39.390 --> 00:25:42.330
And that tells the system
that this app takes advantage

00:25:42.330 --> 00:25:44.370
of Daydream when available.

00:25:44.370 --> 00:25:48.540
But if not it, can
operate as a 2D app.

00:25:48.540 --> 00:25:50.020
So with that, you
now kind of have

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:52.790
an idea of what are you
building-- an app that's

00:25:52.790 --> 00:25:55.540
meant entirely to be a
Daydream app from the ground

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:58.510
up, which we think is going to
be the vast majority of stuff,

00:25:58.510 --> 00:26:01.100
or are you going to introduce
a Daydream experience

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:02.307
to your existing app?

00:26:02.307 --> 00:26:03.140
And so you're ready.

00:26:03.140 --> 00:26:06.367
With these choices, you're ready
to submit your app for review.

00:26:06.367 --> 00:26:08.700
And so I'm going to invite
Alex, who is going to tell us

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:11.512
about what happens after that.

00:26:11.512 --> 00:26:12.720
ALEX RUSSELL: Thanks, Brahim.

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:13.984
BRAHIM ELBOUCHIKHI: Thank you.

00:26:13.984 --> 00:26:16.300
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:16.300 --> 00:26:21.530
ALEX RUSSELL: All right, so
you've declared the intent.

00:26:21.530 --> 00:26:25.619
You want to be in the
Home Launcher environment.

00:26:25.619 --> 00:26:27.660
So, as Brahim was saying,
you declare the intent.

00:26:27.660 --> 00:26:29.659
And when you do this,
this will trigger a review

00:26:29.659 --> 00:26:31.860
to make sure that it's
actually a VR app.

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:33.749
This is similar to
Android Wear, where

00:26:33.749 --> 00:26:35.540
they check to make sure
things are actually

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:38.120
watch apps, or Android
TV, where they're

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:40.100
looking for actual TV apps.

00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:45.100
So because we care
about you understanding

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:47.366
exactly what that
review involves,

00:26:47.366 --> 00:26:48.490
I'll tell you specifically.

00:26:48.490 --> 00:26:51.607
There's 13 criteria
that we're looking for.

00:26:51.607 --> 00:26:53.190
And if we add
additional things, we'll

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:55.340
be communicating
that out as well.

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:57.494
Obviously, we care a
lot about transparency.

00:26:57.494 --> 00:26:59.160
We want everyone to
know what's going on

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:00.159
with the review process.

00:27:00.159 --> 00:27:03.020
And it's all pretty
straightforward stuff.

00:27:03.020 --> 00:27:05.480
So let's start off
with the basics.

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:08.140
And with basics, we just
have one through four.

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:09.390
This one doesn't really count.

00:27:09.390 --> 00:27:10.849
This is more this
kind of baseline.

00:27:10.849 --> 00:27:12.598
Your app needs to
actually install and run

00:27:12.598 --> 00:27:13.933
so that the reviewer can use it.

00:27:13.933 --> 00:27:17.230
Although, surprisingly,
sometimes that's not the case.

00:27:17.230 --> 00:27:20.510
Assuming that works out, moving
on to the actual review--

00:27:20.510 --> 00:27:21.210
performance.

00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:22.990
So does the app
maintain 60 frames

00:27:22.990 --> 00:27:25.170
per second over
long play sessions

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:27.020
on a Daydream-ready phone?

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:29.479
We'll be following up with more
details about exactly which

00:27:29.479 --> 00:27:32.144
phone models we'll be testing on
and how you can replicate these

00:27:32.144 --> 00:27:33.024
tests on your side.

00:27:33.024 --> 00:27:34.440
So there shouldn't
be any question

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:37.362
about if the test
was run correctly.

00:27:37.362 --> 00:27:38.570
But this is really important.

00:27:38.570 --> 00:27:40.310
It's important
for users enjoying

00:27:40.310 --> 00:27:43.240
VR and the success of
the overall platform

00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:46.065
and the quality of experience we
want to have in the ecosystem.

00:27:48.720 --> 00:27:52.010
Number two, as Brahim was
saying, never go to 2D.

00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:53.210
This is kind of a tautology.

00:27:53.210 --> 00:27:55.510
It's like a VR app stays in VR.

00:27:55.510 --> 00:27:57.830
But it's really important
not to accidentally throw up

00:27:57.830 --> 00:28:00.900
a dialog box or something
in 2D when the user has

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:02.150
their phone in their headset.

00:28:02.150 --> 00:28:03.760
It's a really bad experience.

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:06.580
In particular, if you ask for
particular permissions, things

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:09.070
like camera or contacts,
those will actually

00:28:09.070 --> 00:28:13.180
currently trigger a 2D dialog
box in VR, which is not good.

00:28:13.180 --> 00:28:16.051
So we'll be looking
for things like that.

00:28:16.051 --> 00:28:18.050
And if you do need to ask
for those permissions,

00:28:18.050 --> 00:28:20.740
just doing it in a 2D
flow before the user gets

00:28:20.740 --> 00:28:21.794
to being in VR.

00:28:21.794 --> 00:28:23.210
And you'll know
when you're in VR,

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:25.043
so then you know not
to call the permission.

00:28:25.043 --> 00:28:27.761
Number three-- this one's
pretty direct-- App stays

00:28:27.761 --> 00:28:28.510
in landscape mode.

00:28:28.510 --> 00:28:30.676
Obviously, if the user moves
their head to the side,

00:28:30.676 --> 00:28:33.370
you don't want the
phone reoriented.

00:28:33.370 --> 00:28:36.190
Number four, also, you'd
think it's very direct,

00:28:36.190 --> 00:28:39.090
but a lot of apps are
currently doing this wrong.

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:40.960
Use immersive fullscreen mode.

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:43.750
You don't want to have the
status bar and system bar

00:28:43.750 --> 00:28:46.470
on screen when the users in VR.

00:28:46.470 --> 00:28:48.779
Some people will accidentally
go into lights-out mode,

00:28:48.779 --> 00:28:49.570
where it dims them.

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:51.770
You can still kind of see them
in your peripheral vision,

00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:53.978
and depending on the lenses,
you might really see it.

00:28:53.978 --> 00:28:57.010
So you want to use, obviously,
the entire screen to show

00:28:57.010 --> 00:28:59.790
your VR content.

00:28:59.790 --> 00:29:02.080
So that gets us through
the super basic stuff.

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:05.130
Moving on to comfort--
items 5 through 10.

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:07.680
Number five, users
can focus on elements.

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:11.430
So in VR, you're showing stuff
stereoscopically with lenses.

00:29:11.430 --> 00:29:14.360
If you bring objects
in less than a meter,

00:29:14.360 --> 00:29:16.100
but especially like
getting in that kind

00:29:16.100 --> 00:29:18.130
of 10-centimeter
range, a lot of users

00:29:18.130 --> 00:29:20.310
aren't going be able to
focus on them, especially

00:29:20.310 --> 00:29:22.800
if this is like a critical
piece of interface

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:25.250
or your menu or
something like that.

00:29:25.250 --> 00:29:28.370
If the reviewer sees
that they're actually

00:29:28.370 --> 00:29:31.580
having to go somewhat cross-eyed
and they can't actually

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:35.289
focus on objects, that could
trigger this being an issue.

00:29:35.289 --> 00:29:37.330
So, as a general rule,
for really critical stuff,

00:29:37.330 --> 00:29:38.970
you want to keep
it more than half

00:29:38.970 --> 00:29:40.349
a meter away from the user.

00:29:40.349 --> 00:29:41.890
And in your own
testing, you're going

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:44.070
to realize this
because you'll have

00:29:44.070 --> 00:29:46.980
trouble using your own app.

00:29:46.980 --> 00:29:49.670
Number six, app
maintains head tracking.

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:51.680
So similar to
performance, you really

00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:54.309
never want to freeze
the camera in VR.

00:29:54.309 --> 00:29:55.850
As a user's moving
their head around,

00:29:55.850 --> 00:29:57.890
you have to always update.

00:29:57.890 --> 00:30:00.759
But something that we
found is a lot of apps,

00:30:00.759 --> 00:30:02.050
they'll have great performance.

00:30:02.050 --> 00:30:04.400
But then when they're
loading a new scene,

00:30:04.400 --> 00:30:06.380
the app will freeze
for maybe half a second

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:08.749
or a second as that
new scene loads in.

00:30:08.749 --> 00:30:10.790
And it's not because the
app had bad performance.

00:30:10.790 --> 00:30:12.882
It's just they
actually were done.

00:30:12.882 --> 00:30:14.340
Now they had to
load the new scene,

00:30:14.340 --> 00:30:15.756
so they didn't
have an opportunity

00:30:15.756 --> 00:30:17.160
to maintain head tracking.

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:20.660
So those things can still make
people really not feel good,

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:23.950
like even just a second here
and there can be a problem.

00:30:23.950 --> 00:30:26.582
So if you're going to
have to load a new scene

00:30:26.582 --> 00:30:28.290
and you're not doing
asynchronous loading

00:30:28.290 --> 00:30:32.075
or something, just fade to black
or fade to any solid color,

00:30:32.075 --> 00:30:34.700
so the user doesn't have objects
onscreen that they can realize

00:30:34.700 --> 00:30:35.908
the head tracking turned off.

00:30:37.955 --> 00:30:39.580
If you actually want
to play with this,

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:41.621
in the Cardboard design
lab, we have a demo where

00:30:41.621 --> 00:30:44.440
tracking turns off randomly.

00:30:44.440 --> 00:30:49.080
It doesn't feel great, if
you want to experience it.

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:51.590
Also on the topic of not
feeling great, stable horizon

00:30:51.590 --> 00:30:53.875
line-- if the app has
a visible horizon,

00:30:53.875 --> 00:30:56.670
it needs to remain stable.

00:30:56.670 --> 00:31:00.830
A quick example of
this-- I apologize.

00:31:00.830 --> 00:31:02.830
Let's keep it on screen
for a little bit longer.

00:31:02.830 --> 00:31:04.830
And then you don't want
to drop frames like that

00:31:04.830 --> 00:31:07.660
either-- also not good.

00:31:07.660 --> 00:31:11.160
Yes, so this is a big thing
for user comfort as well.

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:13.640
Then number eight, users
initiate movement--

00:31:13.640 --> 00:31:17.500
so if users are
moving around a scene,

00:31:17.500 --> 00:31:21.280
you want them to actually
point and click to teleport,

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:25.910
or use the trackpad on the
controller to walk forward.

00:31:25.910 --> 00:31:28.360
Even if it's a roller
coaster or the entire point

00:31:28.360 --> 00:31:30.693
as they're getting in this
car and then the car is going

00:31:30.693 --> 00:31:32.520
to take them around,
they should click

00:31:32.520 --> 00:31:33.916
to start the roller coaster.

00:31:33.916 --> 00:31:35.290
So at no point
should you just be

00:31:35.290 --> 00:31:36.820
kind of randomly
grabbing the user

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:38.820
and flinging them
around to various parts

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:41.920
of your application without
them indicating that's actually

00:31:41.920 --> 00:31:43.010
what they wanted.

00:31:43.010 --> 00:31:44.990
They shouldn't be
surprised by that,

00:31:44.990 --> 00:31:47.890
because it's part of the
surprise that actually affects

00:31:47.890 --> 00:31:48.940
your level of comfort.

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:51.220
It's sort of similar to driving
a car, you don't get car sick.

00:31:51.220 --> 00:31:52.900
But when you're a
passenger in a car, you do.

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:54.858
Because when you're
driving, you can anticipate

00:31:54.858 --> 00:31:57.550
how the car's going to feel.

00:31:57.550 --> 00:31:59.884
Another other example
of teleportation,

00:31:59.884 --> 00:32:02.050
or any of these other
different types of locomotion,

00:32:02.050 --> 00:32:04.310
we have that in last
year's Cardboard design lab

00:32:04.310 --> 00:32:08.030
as well, where the user's
clicking to move about.

00:32:08.030 --> 00:32:11.980
Number nine, honestly
represent content in the app.

00:32:11.980 --> 00:32:14.470
Descriptions and
screenshots should

00:32:14.470 --> 00:32:17.570
be generally representative
of what your app's about.

00:32:17.570 --> 00:32:20.980
So imagine you have this
great meditation app,

00:32:20.980 --> 00:32:22.820
and it's about hanging
out on the beach.

00:32:22.820 --> 00:32:26.270
and the user's very relaxed,
and the palm trees are swaying.

00:32:26.270 --> 00:32:29.930
And then 15 minutes
in or so, a zombie

00:32:29.930 --> 00:32:33.030
shows up wielding a chainsaw.

00:32:33.030 --> 00:32:34.160
That's fine.

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:37.340
But you should somehow indicate
in the description or title

00:32:37.340 --> 00:32:39.510
or screenshots that that
was going to happen.

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:42.484
We don't want just
blatant surprises and kind

00:32:42.484 --> 00:32:43.400
of trolling like that.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:47.560
So that covers comfort.

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:53.520
Now on to Daydream integration
for the final three.

00:32:53.520 --> 00:32:56.600
Number 10, app uses the
Daydream controller.

00:32:56.600 --> 00:32:59.634
So the Daydream controller
comes with every single viewer.

00:32:59.634 --> 00:33:01.300
Also, the Daydream
controller's required

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:02.258
to use the home screen.

00:33:02.258 --> 00:33:03.860
So when the user
launches your app,

00:33:03.860 --> 00:33:07.160
we know that they're holding
that controller in their hand.

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:08.680
We want all of the
apps on Daydream

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:11.410
to take advantage
of the controller.

00:33:11.410 --> 00:33:13.470
In particular, if
you're bringing an app

00:33:13.470 --> 00:33:17.510
over from Cardboard, just using
the controller as a clicker

00:33:17.510 --> 00:33:21.300
doesn't actually count as taking
advantage of the controller.

00:33:21.300 --> 00:33:22.980
We want the
controller to be used

00:33:22.980 --> 00:33:24.859
for targeting input and
not the user's head,

00:33:24.859 --> 00:33:27.150
since we now have an additional
[INAUDIBLE] controller.

00:33:30.350 --> 00:33:32.784
Number 11, app has a VR icon.

00:33:32.784 --> 00:33:34.200
So users are going
to be launching

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:36.040
your app from inside
of VR, so obviously you

00:33:36.040 --> 00:33:38.050
need to provide this.

00:33:38.050 --> 00:33:39.320
There's two aspects.

00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:41.580
There's a background element
and a foreground element.

00:33:41.580 --> 00:33:43.330
The reviewers are just
going to be looking

00:33:43.330 --> 00:33:45.413
for little simple things,
like you actually filled

00:33:45.413 --> 00:33:47.010
out the full texture.

00:33:47.010 --> 00:33:49.300
So if you only paint
the front, and the sides

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:51.770
and back are white, that
might trigger something.

00:33:51.770 --> 00:33:54.230
Also, it kind of sort
of shimmers in VR

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:56.860
if you didn't paint
the whole thing,

00:33:56.860 --> 00:33:58.060
but pretty straightforward.

00:33:58.060 --> 00:34:01.500
And we'll publish all
the specs for this.

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:04.562
And then you have a
360-photosphere screenshot.

00:34:04.562 --> 00:34:06.520
We'll be using these in
a few different places.

00:34:06.520 --> 00:34:11.618
One is in Play VR-- Play Store
VR-- as the user looks around.

00:34:11.618 --> 00:34:13.909
As they're browsing apps,
this will be the environments

00:34:13.909 --> 00:34:15.719
that your app is in.

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:17.469
And then, also, in
2D, we may use these

00:34:17.469 --> 00:34:20.010
as like a Magic Window, where
you can kind of move your phone

00:34:20.010 --> 00:34:21.100
around and see the app.

00:34:24.250 --> 00:34:27.130
And then generating
a 360 environment

00:34:27.130 --> 00:34:28.707
is actually really simple.

00:34:28.707 --> 00:34:30.290
Depending on what
game engine you use,

00:34:30.290 --> 00:34:31.739
you find the correct plugin.

00:34:31.739 --> 00:34:33.155
In this case, it's
showing Unity--

00:34:33.155 --> 00:34:34.909
so bringing in a
plugin, where you

00:34:34.909 --> 00:34:36.770
can do a capture of panorama.

00:34:36.770 --> 00:34:39.370
You're just attaching that
script onto a game object.

00:34:39.370 --> 00:34:40.440
Then you launch the game.

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:42.439
In this case, you just
hit a key on the keyboard

00:34:42.439 --> 00:34:45.310
and it generates the
photosphere for you.

00:34:45.310 --> 00:34:47.460
So you can sort of stage
your shots that way.

00:34:47.460 --> 00:34:51.270
And these plugins are available
across all the game engines,

00:34:51.270 --> 00:34:53.929
and we'll be posting
links to them as well.

00:34:53.929 --> 00:34:56.449
So that's how you get
listed in Play VR.

00:34:56.449 --> 00:34:59.330
But that leaves sort of the
broader and more interesting

00:34:59.330 --> 00:35:01.990
question of what should
you actually make?

00:35:01.990 --> 00:35:03.630
To which, to some
extent, our answer

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:06.190
is like, well, it's
up to you guys.

00:35:06.190 --> 00:35:10.030
You can be imaginative,
and that's what's exciting.

00:35:10.030 --> 00:35:13.350
But there are a few things that
we're really excited about,

00:35:13.350 --> 00:35:16.700
so we wanted to sort
of share some of that.

00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:21.230
This isn't based on
really firm data yet,

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:22.860
because it's so early for VR.

00:35:22.860 --> 00:35:25.346
A lot of this is kind of a
mixture of our experiences

00:35:25.346 --> 00:35:27.220
and intuition and
observing other things that

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:29.330
are happening with apps.

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:31.910
So this is going to
evolve a little bit.

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:35.730
It's a little bit mushier
than, say, the 13 criteria.

00:35:35.730 --> 00:35:38.730
But the first thing that
we're thinking about

00:35:38.730 --> 00:35:42.390
is overall, what
experience do you want

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:44.650
users to have with your app?

00:35:44.650 --> 00:35:46.620
We're finding this
is like an early way

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:48.400
that apps seem to be
bucketing themselves

00:35:48.400 --> 00:35:50.070
into different categories in VR.

00:35:50.070 --> 00:35:51.620
Do you want the
app to be relaxing,

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:53.280
or do you want it
to be thrilling?

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:55.259
And it's not the
case that one of them

00:35:55.259 --> 00:35:56.800
is necessarily better
than the other.

00:35:56.800 --> 00:35:58.790
They're just very different.

00:35:58.790 --> 00:36:01.050
So roller coaster
apps are actually

00:36:01.050 --> 00:36:04.275
very popular on Google Play
right now for Cardboard.

00:36:04.275 --> 00:36:06.400
But just like how roller
coasters in the real world

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:08.234
aren't for everyone,
virtual roller coasters

00:36:08.234 --> 00:36:09.066
aren't for everyone.

00:36:09.066 --> 00:36:10.820
They have their market,
and other people

00:36:10.820 --> 00:36:13.150
aren't super interested
in roller coasters.

00:36:13.150 --> 00:36:15.260
So something we've
been thinking about

00:36:15.260 --> 00:36:17.870
is trying to have a
little bit more structure

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:22.540
to this notion of what the
physiological experience

00:36:22.540 --> 00:36:24.010
of the app is.

00:36:24.010 --> 00:36:26.940
So we're referring to
this is motion intensity.

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:31.270
And currently we're bucketing
into three categories.

00:36:31.270 --> 00:36:33.000
This might evolve
a bit over time.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.210
We think that three is
probably useful to think about

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:36.810
as you're thinking
about the motion

00:36:36.810 --> 00:36:39.210
intensity of your
application-- so no motion,

00:36:39.210 --> 00:36:42.120
moderate, and intense.

00:36:42.120 --> 00:36:45.370
And to help me explain
this, I actually

00:36:45.370 --> 00:36:49.580
have a prop, because
sometimes this is complicated.

00:36:49.580 --> 00:36:53.390
So here, this is the user.

00:36:53.390 --> 00:36:56.720
It is also the camera
in your game engine,

00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:58.610
and it's really
important to-- honestly,

00:36:58.610 --> 00:37:00.276
I think the game
engines should actually

00:37:00.276 --> 00:37:02.665
make them look like heads,
so that people remember

00:37:02.665 --> 00:37:04.456
that this is the user
in their game engine,

00:37:04.456 --> 00:37:05.850
and not just a camera.

00:37:05.850 --> 00:37:08.920
Or as our filmmaker
Jessica likes to say,

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:11.630
the cameras are
made out of people.

00:37:11.630 --> 00:37:13.830
So these can consciously
choose to look around

00:37:13.830 --> 00:37:15.330
in any action they want.

00:37:15.330 --> 00:37:17.270
But then, as a
developer, you can also

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:18.790
choose to move these around.

00:37:18.790 --> 00:37:19.949
So, Brahim, heads up.

00:37:19.949 --> 00:37:21.490
BRAHIM ELBOUCHIKHI:
You want it back?

00:37:21.490 --> 00:37:23.990
ALEX RUSSELL: Yeah, sure.

00:37:23.990 --> 00:37:25.310
Toss that out there.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:27.720
Yeah, so, as a developer,
you want to be careful.

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:28.220
That's OK.

00:37:28.220 --> 00:37:29.620
I've got another one.

00:37:29.620 --> 00:37:31.740
The podium is actually
full of heads right now.

00:37:31.740 --> 00:37:33.370
It's very weird.

00:37:33.370 --> 00:37:35.420
So thinking about
motion intensity,

00:37:35.420 --> 00:37:38.290
no motion is just the user
is moving their head around.

00:37:38.290 --> 00:37:40.490
The developer's
not doing anything.

00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:44.330
So things like watching
a movie, those types

00:37:44.330 --> 00:37:45.750
of apps where you're still.

00:37:48.640 --> 00:37:51.205
In terms of moderate
motion, the user

00:37:51.205 --> 00:37:53.466
is moving in two
degrees virtually.

00:37:53.466 --> 00:37:55.090
So they can move
their head themselves,

00:37:55.090 --> 00:37:57.664
but say they're in
a car or they've

00:37:57.664 --> 00:37:59.330
indicated they want
to walk, they're not

00:37:59.330 --> 00:38:00.205
walking in real life.

00:38:00.205 --> 00:38:02.190
But they're using the
controller to walk.

00:38:02.190 --> 00:38:05.830
So virtually just kind of
traveling in one plane, that's

00:38:05.830 --> 00:38:07.010
moderate.

00:38:07.010 --> 00:38:09.000
Limited acceleration
and deceleration--

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:10.920
If you accelerate
really, really fast, that

00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:12.230
would make it more intense.

00:38:12.230 --> 00:38:14.656
Also, if there's a lot of
objects coming at them,

00:38:14.656 --> 00:38:16.030
that could make
it more intense--

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:17.530
the combination of
the things coming

00:38:17.530 --> 00:38:18.880
at you with you moving forward.

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:22.390
And then final category
for intense, this

00:38:22.390 --> 00:38:25.410
is where you get into the
virtual flying and driving

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:27.130
and roller coasters
and spaceships

00:38:27.130 --> 00:38:29.360
and that kind of stuff,
where in addition to the user

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:32.760
moving their head around, the
developer is also putting them

00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:34.690
in a space ship,
where it is causing

00:38:34.690 --> 00:38:39.510
three to six degrees of motion.

00:38:39.510 --> 00:38:42.226
So we're still sort of figuring
out the details on this.

00:38:42.226 --> 00:38:45.180
I don't actually need
the head anymore.

00:38:45.180 --> 00:38:48.435
One way to think
about it is it's

00:38:48.435 --> 00:38:50.700
the difference between
sitting, walking, and flying.

00:38:50.700 --> 00:38:52.575
It's a little bit more
complicated than that.

00:38:52.575 --> 00:38:55.322
Things like if there's
no floor present,

00:38:55.322 --> 00:38:56.780
even if the user's
not moving, that

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:58.840
could be slightly disorienting.

00:38:58.840 --> 00:39:00.300
So not having a
floor could cause

00:39:00.300 --> 00:39:03.360
it to go between no
motion to moderate.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:06.290
Or even if they're still and
there's very large objects

00:39:06.290 --> 00:39:08.140
coming at them, that
can give the perception

00:39:08.140 --> 00:39:09.920
that you're moving forward,
because you sort of lose

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:10.880
your grounding.

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:13.400
So that could also cause it
to go from no to moderate.

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:16.650
So we'll be publishing
more details about this

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:20.660
as we think more about how apps
would fall into these buckets.

00:39:20.660 --> 00:39:23.900
We think it's important to have
the sort of physiological way

00:39:23.900 --> 00:39:25.401
for users to think
about categories,

00:39:25.401 --> 00:39:27.941
because some people are really
interested in some categories,

00:39:27.941 --> 00:39:29.870
and other people are
interested in others.

00:39:29.870 --> 00:39:33.840
So that's one way of thinking
about how to group apps.

00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:36.140
But what about the genres?

00:39:36.140 --> 00:39:38.420
What are the different
types of VR apps,

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:40.260
more in terms of content?

00:39:40.260 --> 00:39:41.890
And that's sort of interesting.

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:47.520
It's like the genres are still
largely being discovered in VR.

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:49.620
We seem to see a few things.

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:51.740
In particular, games
and entertainment

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:53.150
seems to be really big.

00:39:53.150 --> 00:39:56.750
But something we're
finding is this

00:39:56.750 --> 00:39:58.480
is a general-purpose
computing platform.

00:39:58.480 --> 00:40:00.250
This is Android.

00:40:00.250 --> 00:40:02.000
So games and
entertainment are great.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:03.710
But also VR can
be about much more

00:40:03.710 --> 00:40:05.020
than games and entertainment.

00:40:05.020 --> 00:40:07.370
And we're in the
very, very early days

00:40:07.370 --> 00:40:10.910
of starting to see that emerge.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:13.610
So here's some quick
ideas of things

00:40:13.610 --> 00:40:16.200
that we're excited about.

00:40:16.200 --> 00:40:18.050
Education is really interesting.

00:40:18.050 --> 00:40:21.280
Google's done a lot of work with
expeditions and primary school.

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:25.230
But even education for higher
education is super interesting.

00:40:25.230 --> 00:40:26.840
Learning physics in
VR could be great.

00:40:26.840 --> 00:40:30.060
Learning organic chemistry in
VR could be really interesting.

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:32.170
Being able to engage the
user's spatial memory

00:40:32.170 --> 00:40:35.640
could actually have impact
on their ability to learn,

00:40:35.640 --> 00:40:38.450
and there might be some
real advantages to having

00:40:38.450 --> 00:40:41.720
a 3D environment for education.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:44.300
Architecture is something
that often comes up

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:46.030
and we're very excited
about-- not just

00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:47.613
in the professional
use case, but also

00:40:47.613 --> 00:40:51.170
users being able to model
things and play around.

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:58.530
Music is just starting to
emerge as a category for VR.

00:40:58.530 --> 00:41:00.700
I don't know how many
people played Audio Shields.

00:41:00.700 --> 00:41:02.040
It's really neat.

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:05.860
Also Daydream Labs has some very
cool experiments with music.

00:41:05.860 --> 00:41:08.650
A lot of these, they're still
a little bit more traditional.

00:41:08.650 --> 00:41:11.020
But imagine like
you're a DJ in VR

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:13.560
and you're going beyond
the physical constraints

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:15.290
of a turntable.

00:41:15.290 --> 00:41:17.710
That could be really neat.

00:41:17.710 --> 00:41:20.350
You can really play with
the concept of music.

00:41:20.350 --> 00:41:23.230
You can even have the user
dancing, like the music

00:41:23.230 --> 00:41:24.750
responding to them dance.

00:41:24.750 --> 00:41:27.010
So I think this
sort of brings us

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:31.460
to the topic of like
going beyond reality.

00:41:31.460 --> 00:41:33.750
A lot of VR apps
right now are awfully

00:41:33.750 --> 00:41:36.390
grounded in reality,
which is weird,

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:38.470
because you don't have to be.

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:40.060
So there's lots
of things that you

00:41:40.060 --> 00:41:43.250
could do that just simply can't
happen in the real life-- so

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:45.180
data visualization,
of course; being

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:48.260
able to understand
complex data, which

00:41:48.260 --> 00:41:49.990
we haven't been
able to do before,

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:52.990
unless you build lots
of models about it.

00:41:52.990 --> 00:41:55.520
Meditation could be
really interesting.

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:57.960
Music visualizations,
and kind of almost

00:41:57.960 --> 00:42:01.070
synesthetic experience-- playing
with these types of things

00:42:01.070 --> 00:42:03.210
could be very neat.

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:06.300
Also e-sports might
be really interesting.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:08.670
A crowd forming to
watch other people

00:42:08.670 --> 00:42:11.645
to compete at something
that goes beyond reality

00:42:11.645 --> 00:42:13.270
could be a really
compelling use of VR.

00:42:13.270 --> 00:42:15.730
So that's just some
of the initial ideas

00:42:15.730 --> 00:42:18.560
off the top of our head of what
we think we might see emerge.

00:42:18.560 --> 00:42:21.120
But what's exciting is
it seems like every day

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:24.310
we're seeing almost entirely
new app categories come out.

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:28.300
And there's lots of room for
exploration and innovation,

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:31.010
and really, you have an
infinite canvas to explore.

00:42:31.010 --> 00:42:33.440
So with that, thank you.

